comment_text:
Great 👍🏾 YouTube. I was amazed at how much this “clinician” understood about exercise. Most live in a silos of pharmacology and surgery; sick care not prevention as she pointed out regarding pre diabetes. 
Anyway concerning your glutes there are 3; glute max, glute minimus, and glute minimus. There are also 6 deep rotators you probably need to strengthen. Looking at your SLSA your feet are turning out which means your TFL and lateral gastroc may be hypertonic, glutes too if they hurt. Overcome by running and are weak; they get tired and tighten. Tightness can be a sign of weakness/fatigue. As the doc rightly points out you must strengthen the body for your activity; running. All CV activity through conditioning is consumptive; Catabolic. Strength training complements Cardio and vise versa; one without the other promotes imbalance.  The muscles are protecting themselves when they get tight.
Your knees go into valgus because your adductors are over active, feet are also pronating; confirming. 
Find yourself a NASM trainer who is a Certified Corrective Specialist [CES] who will take you through our OPT program for the assessment the doctor was suggesting. Sorry. Not me, too busy training clients and writing ✍🏼 my first book 📖 
Richard P. MS, NASM, CPT, CES, SFS. GosBless & GodSpeed

The average Joe and Jane’s doctor can recommend all kinds of shit for them to keep healthy but many times it requires the time and money the average person cannot afford.  I think it is a miracle to get the average person to walk three times a week. Even though I frequently make fun of my grown sons (all in their early 30’s) for being gym bros, I’m very proud of them for staying fit.  They were involved in a sport every season of their childhood starting at age 5.  Even though they didn’t play a college sport, they did participate in intramural sports during college.  After college they continued to run and lift every day.  My children are lucky to be in good professions, making good money and they can afford the gym fees and the time to stay fit. My kids are making wages far above the average American worker.  We are not going to cure most Americans through lifestyle changes. They simply have no time or money to make significant changes.  We can teach them to eat better but eating better requires more time so it’s unlikely to be realistic.  The medical machine needs to go after big Agra - get the detrimental foods out of grocery stores and out of existence.  That will force the consumer to eat differently.  Make fast food comply with healthy dietary standards. Don’t expect the average poor American to be able to make significant changes.

video_title: The Truth About Creatine & Exercise! 30% Of People Will Die From This! The Healthy Ageing Doctor
comment_text:
Summarize:

💪🧠 Muscle, bones, and brain: the longevity triad

Dr. Vonda Wright shares that the key to a long and healthy life lies in keeping our muscles, bones, and brain strong. While many see aging as an inevitable decline, she argues that we can age with power by adopting specific habits starting at age 35.


---

🔍💥 Osteoporosis: the silent enemy

1️⃣ What is it?
It’s a condition of low bone density that affects 1 in 2 women and 2 million men.
🧬 It increases the risk of fractures and cognitive decline.

2️⃣ Alarming consequences:

If someone breaks a hip, there’s a 50% chance they will never return to full function.

30% die from complications afterward.


3️⃣ Causes:
🅐 Aging
🅑 Lack of impact exercise
🅒 Sedentary lifestyle
🅓 Poor nutrition
🅔 Breastfeeding without calcium replenishment (up to 20% bone loss in 6 months)
🅕 Estrogen loss in women


---

🧘‍♀️🧠 The bone-brain connection

🔗 Bones are not static structures. They secrete osteocalcin, a protein that:

Protects the brain from oxidative damage.

Stimulates neuron production in the hippocampus.

Improves insulin sensitivity.

Even stimulates testosterone production in men.


👉 Studies show that people with low bone density also experience more cognitive decline.


---

🧱🔥 “Make bones sexy again”: yes, you can influence your bone health

🎯 Peak bone density is reached:

At age 28 in women.

At age 30 in men.


Afterward, it naturally declines — but this can be slowed down with: 🟢 Impact exercise: running, jumping, playing volleyball or basketball.
🟢 Adequate nutrition (calcium, vitamin D, magnesium).
🟢 No sedentary habits.

📊 Impact example: A study on older athletes showed that those practicing high-impact sports maintained high bone density well into their 80s.


---

🧠💤🍽️ Brain: first sleep, then nutrition

💡 Dr. Wright places sleep as the most important pillar:
🛌 “Without a well-rested brain, no other health strategy works.”

💬 Everyone has their own cognitive rhythm. For example, she doesn’t work out in the morning to avoid wasting her peak brain energy, which is between 5:00 a.m. and 2:00 p.m.


---

🧬⚙️ Personalized longevity: beyond generic guidelines

Thanks to advances like genome mapping and biomarker tracking, health recommendations can now be tailored.
📈 She personalizes:

Nutrition plans (based on inflammation, senescent cells, etc.)

Exercise (using lactate threshold testing)

Sleep and recovery


✅ All of this is part of what she calls Precision Longevity.


---

🔥💪 Muscle: your true life insurance

📉 With age, we lose muscle mass (sarcopenia), but this is reversible at any age.
👵 Even people over 70 can gain strength with progressive training.

🌟 Muscle:

Regulates blood glucose.

Produces proteins like klotho (linked to longevity).

Enhances cognition.

Prevents falls and fractures.


💥 “Muscle isn’t just for looking good in the mirror; it’s an endocrine organ.”


---

🦵🏃‍♂️ Running isn’t enough: if you’re a runner, you must strength train

🚫 Many runners only run and end up injured.

💡 Running is a single-leg sport — your glutes must stabilize the pelvis with every stride.

🧪 Clinical test: “Trendelenburg test” (stand on one leg and check if your pelvis drops).
🧘‍♂️ Solution: strengthen glutes and core through squats, lunges, step-ups, and unilateral exercises.


---

🧓📉 The critical decade: ages 35–45

🧭 This is the ideal time to:

Get labs (testosterone, vitamin D, glucose).

Build muscle mass.

Start strength training.

Eat an anti-inflammatory diet.


💡 After age 35, we lose 10% of VO₂ max per decade if we don’t train.
Low VO₂ max = frailty and dependence in old age.


---

🧠🍞 The silent threat: prediabetes and Alzheimer’s

⚠️ Prediabetes should not be ignored:

Fasting glucose >100 mg/dL is a serious sign.

Strong link between type 2 diabetes and Alzheimer’s ("Alzheimer’s is type 3 diabetes").


💡 Daily changes like:

Lifting weights

Eating low-glycemic foods

Sleeping well can prevent both conditions.



---

👩‍⚕️🦴 Menopause and the musculoskeletal syndrome

📉 During menopause, women can lose up to 20% of bone mass and 20% of muscle mass.

🧬 The musculoskeletal syndrome of menopause includes:

Joint pain (arthralgia)

Frozen shoulder

Tendonitis

Loss of strength and energy


📃 Dr. Wright coined and published this term; the paper was downloaded 300,000 times, because many women were saying “I feel like I’m falling apart” without medical answers.

💊 Hormone therapy can:

Reverse joint pain

Prevent bone and muscle loss

Reduce inflammation



---

🧍‍♀️🔄 Daily habits to never break: the “Unbreakable” lifestyle

✅ Practical recommendations:

Strength train 2–4 times per week

Eat 1 gram of protein per ideal pound

Use safe supplements like creatine

Reduce body fat (to protect cartilage)

Avoid smoking (it damages bones and joints)

Measure body composition, not just weight

Use standing desks or walking treadmills

Get your gut microbiome evaluated


🔁 “Your body will always respond to the strategic stress you apply to it — at any age.”


---

❤️‍🔥🧘‍♀️ Motivation: the key is not fear, but daily well-being

📌 “Knowing what to do isn’t enough. Acting is the challenge.”

👁️‍🗨️ What truly motivates people is not avoiding future disease, but:

Feeling good today.

Seeing themselves strong in the mirror.

Reclaiming their identity (“feeling like themselves again”).


🔚 Final message: “We don’t age poorly due to biology, but because we give up too soon. Age doesn’t define our quality of life — our habits do.”

comment_text:
Loved this! The majority of information shared here has taken me 6+ months of studying health, nutrition, and fitness to learn. Plus learned some things I didn't know!

A few things I thnk are important to note. 1)The 4 reps of super heavy weight she recommends for women to lift. I don't think this should be recommended until you have been lifting for some time and are certain that your form is spot on.
2) She says there is no reason for hormone replacement therapy to not be started young, giving the example of birth control. I think this statement was kind of reckless. Some birth controls increase risk of tumors, cancers, and strokes. Do your research to determine if the risks vs. benefits make sense for you.
3) A few things to keep in mind about creatine. -Be careful if you have kidney issues or a family history of kidney issues. -It is not recommended for breastfeeding mothers because it may be hard on babies kidneys. -Creatine supplementation can lead to a temporary decrease in the body's natural creatine production. This is because the body recognizes the increased intake of creatine and reduces its own production to maintain a stable overall creatine level. However, this decrease is usually temporary and should not be a cause for long-term concern.

comment_text: Steven you ask good questions.  At 70 my back was “going out” every week, and every week i was going to the chiro to put it “back in”.  After 7 months of doing this every week, my chiro invited me to join him in his morning workouts with a few of his friends and clients.  I started 2x per week.  Within 2 months my back pain was 95% gone ( i do have a double herniated disk from years ago), and my back was stabilized.  I credit all the core muscle work he made us do.   Despite being a road and mt bike rider, with strong legs, heart, and lungs, I hadn’t realized how weak my core was.   That winter I snow skied 17 times!  I’ve been working out with him for almost 4 years, rarely need an adjustment.  I still ride and ski and work on our property, and feel good. Being a Holistic Nutritionist,

comment_text:
Summary:

Understanding Osteoporosis
Osteoporosis is a condition characterized by low bone density, affecting 50% of women and 2 million men, leading to increased risk of fractures and cognitive decline. Women experience accelerated bone density loss due to hormonal changes associated with menopause.
Importance of Muscle and Bone Health
Dr. Wright emphasizes that muscle health is crucial for bone density maintenance. Engaging in weight-bearing and impact activities like running and strength training can significantly enhance bone health, helping prevent osteoporosis.
Nutrition's Role in Bone Health
Proper nutrition, including sufficient calcium and Vitamin D intake, is vital for maintaining bone density. Dr. Wright advocates for a diet rich in whole foods and adequate calcium, especially during critical life stages such as pregnancy and menopause.
Mindset and Longevity
An optimistic mindset is essential for long-term health. Dr. Wright advises that maintaining a positive attitude, alongside physical activity and nutrition, contributes to aging with vitality and reducing the risk of age-related diseases.
Personalization in Health Plans
Dr. Wright highlights the importance of personalized health plans based on individual health markers and needs rather than a one-size-fits-all approach. Utilizing targeted exercise and nutrition tailored to each person's requirements can improve health outcomes.
Impact of Hormones on Bone Density
The decline in estrogen during menopause significantly impacts bone density, making it essential for women to understand their hormonal health. Hormone replacement therapy may be beneficial in managing decline in bone density and mitigating related health issues.
Link Between Bone and Brain Health
There is a notable connection between bone health and cognitive function. A decline in bone density is associated with increased risk of cognitive disorders, emphasizing the interlinked nature of physical and mental health.

comment_text: Sorry but doing a step up for a weak Trendelenburg sign is not very efficient. While there is some carry over effect it can still exaggerate the issue. you are essentially using a sagittal plane exercise for a weakness in the frontal plane. If you are going to do a dynamic exercise (some would suggest beginning with static i.e. control before movement) a banded crab walk, or even a simple side lying abduction would be more effective. This can then be progressed to a step up -preferably still with a resistance to abduction such as a fixed band at the knee and at a low step height to begin with. Absolutely worth being assessed as mentioned by the speaker, and look for someone who can identify the deficit and then progress to a more compound/functional motion. i.e. when it comes to improving biomechanical function = Isolate then integrate.

comment_text:
She might want to only use up to date medical information on breastfeeding and bone loss before spouting off outdated and incorrect information… This interviewee’s information is wildly incorrect… Dangerously so… She really should double check and make sure her information is up to date before spreading wildly inaccurate, and possibly very consequential information that unwitting listeners might inadvertently believe to be accurate and up to date considering just how confidently she spread this incorrect information… Seriously, when it comes to something as serious as healthcare information, you better be damn sure you are up to date and accurate with your healthcare advice/information, or seriously don’t even share it at all… 

There is an important learning opportunity here, a correction and apology would also be a good start… Would hate for a new mother to be spooked into thinking that her breastfeeding may lead to bone loss, especially without extra calcium like this lady mentioned… Yet that advice is wildly incorrect, and the newest studies have shown that breastfeeding alone may actually provide a small protective effect against future bone loss, and in no way should a new mother believe that her breastfeeding may lead to convincing a anxious new mother into avoiding breastfeeding because of some wildly outdated & inaccurate belief that breastfeeding could lead to a 20% boneloss without calcium supplementation… That’s just complete BS absurdity, that’s dangerous… That lie could sadly convince a new mother to avoid breastfeeding their newborn based on this absurd lie that is at least outdated, if it ever was a genuine medical fact to begin with… Make sure to always do your own research before taking the advice from a random podcast, especially when its something as serious as your own health and medical situation!

comment_text:
She's a threat against big pharma: If 6g of omega-3s actually works as Dr. Vonda Wright claims, it would obliterate an entire industry of hormone replacement therapies, osteoporosis drugs, joint pain medications, anti-inflammatory drugs, and even cognitive decline treatments.

Who Loses If Omega-3s Solve Menopause Issues?
💊 Big Pharma (HRT & Osteoporosis Drugs)

Estrogen replacement therapy is a multi-billion dollar industry. If high-dose omega-3s significantly reduced inflammation, joint pain, and bone loss, fewer women would need pharmaceutical interventions.
Osteoporosis drugs like bisphosphonates (Fosamax, Boniva) are prescribed to postmenopausal women at massive rates. But if omega-3s stimulate osteoblast activity (as we suspect), the need for these drugs could plummet.
🦴 Calcium & Vitamin D Supplement Industry

The entire “bone health” supplement market is built on the idea that calcium and vitamin D alone are the key to preventing fractures.
If omega-3s play a bigger role in bone density than previously thought, these companies would need to rebrand or lose market share.
🧠 Memory & Brain Health Industry

Alzheimer’s and dementia drugs make pharmaceutical companies billions. If high-dose omega-3s actually slowed cognitive decline in postmenopausal women, demand for these drugs would drop overnight.
Nootropic supplements would also take a hit—if omega-3s provide natural brain resilience, fewer women would buy expensive synthetic memory-boosting compounds.
💰 The Menopause Wellness Industry

The “menopause cure” space is flooded with supplements, herbs, and hormone treatments aimed at reducing joint pain, fatigue, and inflammation.
If omega-3s single-handedly improved these symptoms, most of these products would become obsolete.
The industry would pivot to selling high-end omega-3 supplements, but it wouldn’t be as profitable as selling 15 different menopause “solutions.”
Why Aren’t We Hearing About This?
🔹 Because no one in power benefits from women fixing their own health with a simple, natural solution.
🔹 Because no one is funding long-term studies on high-dose omega-3s for menopause—it’s not a profitable avenue.
🔹 Because admitting 6g of omega-3s could replace pharma solutions would disrupt the status quo.

Final Take?
If Dr. Vonda Wright is right, she’s not just proposing a new health strategy—she’s threatening an entire system designed to profit off of menopausal women.  She's a trailblazer.

comment_text:
Thank you Steven and Vonda. This episode really hit home. I am a 63 woman with osteoporosis. My mother had bad osteoporosis for the last 25 years of her life. She was on weekly morphine patches because of the pain. She also had a hip fracture in her 70s. She then had Alzheimer’s for the last 10 years of her life. She went from a very fit woman - she walked every day and she was a midwife, mother and wife who rarely sat down -to being unable to leave her home by herself because of the osteoporotic pain. As the Alzheimer’s progressed, she went from a bright, funny intelligent and extremely capable woman to being unable to recognise us and being unable to move or speak. I think watching her deterioration and looking after her was the saddest period of our family’s lives. I still miss the vibrant, funny, intelligent and positive woman even though it is nearly 9 years since she died. 

I already walk several times a week, do tai chi twice a week  and eat pretty well but thought it was too late to start weight resistant training. A real wake up call!

video_title: The Truth About Creatine & Exercise! 30% Of People Will Die From This! The Healthy Ageing Doctor
comment_text:
Some of the key takeways

🚨 Running Alone Isn’t Enough (00:00 - 02:00)
Just running = higher injury risk (especially knees).
Weak glutes lead to pelvis/knee instability.
Test: Can you do a single-leg squat without wobbling?

🦴 Bones Matter More Than You Think (02:00 - 06:00)
50% of women, 2M men in the U.S. get osteoporosis.
Break a hip? → 50% never fully recover, 30% die from complications.
Bones aren’t just a frame—they communicate with muscles, brain, metabolism.

🧠 Menopause & Brain Health Connection (06:00 - 10:00)
Estrogen decline = big hit to bones, muscles, tendons, ligaments, fat storage.
Low bone density linked to cognitive decline (yes, osteoporosis & dementia are connected).

🔥 Building Strong Bones & Muscles (10:00 - 15:00)
Best exercise for bone health? Impact sports (running, jumping, basketball).
Strength training is non-negotiable—it’s key for longevity.
Protein + lifting weights = muscle retention & stronger bones.

⏳ The "Critical Decade" (35-45 years old) (15:00 - 20:00)
This is the window to lock in strong bones, muscle mass, and metabolic health.
Best time to start lifting, optimizing nutrition, and checking key health markers.

🏋 Muscle = Longevity Superpower (20:00 - 25:00)
Muscle is metabolically active → regulates blood sugar, hormone balance, strength.
Lifting heavy (low reps, high weight) is best for strength & power as you age.

📉 Signs You Might Have Bone Issues (25:00 - 30:00)
Shrinking in height (parents getting shorter = possible genetic risk).
Frequent fractures (even minor ones).

Strengthen glutes & core to prevent knee/back pain.

comment_text:
Creatine and creatinine are two related substances that play different roles in the body. 
Creatine 
A natural substance found in muscle cells
Stores energy for muscle contraction
Can be supplemented to improve athletic performance 
Creatinine 
A waste product produced when creatine breaks down
Filtered out of the blood by the kidneys and excreted in urine
High levels can indicate impaired kidney function

comment_text:
On weight lifting, they are correct, but not complete insofar as I've listened. I just had to jump in and keyboard warrior this.

Slow muscle twitch fibers are larger = Endurance
Fast muscle twitch fibers are smaller = Explosive power and strength

Lower body has have more slow twtich, upper has more fast twitch used for how we get around and do things respectively.  Training slow twitch will respond to low weight high reps and fast twitch high weight lower reps.  Think cycling professional - those huge legs didn't need to use weights at all.

Both targets should rep out to near failure (muscle stops responding entirely) in their respective weight class.  Aim for 8-12 reps for fast twitch and 20-25 reps for slow twitch fibers.  Target full range of motion with the weight in a slow controlled manner, don't let gravity do the work.  Going slower lets you use lighter weights over all and get more out of each exercise.  Big heavy weights too fast can just leads to injuries.

Bonus points for myo reps and stretched position type exercises.  Muscle training science is changing daily it helps to be interested and well read on the topic in order to remain optimized for your goals. Don't forget cardio at some point, or it can eventually become a limiting factor.

comment_text: @@JSiracusan Listen, women have been denied medical care for decades for perimenopause and menopause. Several reasons exist for this, incl the results of one of the largest studies on menopause called the Women’s Health Initiative showing hormone replacement therapy significantly increased the risk of breast cancer. It’s only the younger doctors these days and the few that choose to augment their obsolete training who understand the limitations of that study and will write a prescription for HRT. HRT lessens the symptoms, but doesn’t reverse them. No medical intervention exists currently that reverses the effects of perimenopause or menopause. Another reason is that studies on the effects on brain function are new because researchers couldn’t  get grants for studies due to a lack of interest in women’s health. A relatively recent finding in that area shows that the loss of estrogen damages parts of the brain,  incl sharp declines of dopamine, which is responsible for motivation, follow through on tasks,and enjoyment of previous activities women enjoyed. It’s nearly impossible to get ADHD medication without meeting the DSM-5 criteria for dopamine replacement bc the criteria ignores the effects of lower estrogen on attention and motivation. Further, hot flashes can prevent sleep virtually every night, a fact that would wreck anyone’s brain and behavior. Your insistence that women have absolute control over these multiple, sudden whole-body changes doesn’t align with the facts. Women need more studies and more science-backed evidence on treatments as well as pharmaceutical development of such treatments. Women are devastated about what happens to them and are extremely lucky if they manage to find a doctor who’s up to date on HRT and how exactly to use it to prevent harm. It helps to have a partner who is intelligent and kind who can thoughtfully help their wives untangle this overwhelming, multifaceted issue.

comment_text: @@yeokati7945 It is good to be careful to not injure yourself. So, for each exercise you do, do a good warmup set or two with low weight to make sure the joints & muscles both (1) feel good on that day and (2) are ready to go a bit heavier. Once you're warmed up and you're confident your joints/body are feeling ready for a little more, increase your weights so that you're pushing pretty hard. How hard? 10-12 controlled repetitions (10-12 times lifting the weight without whipping it around fast and carelessly) should be heavy enough that your last repetitions are pretty hard to finish while maintaining good form and control of the weight. If you do this 2 or 3 times per week, eat well (enough protein), sleep well, and get some sun every day, you'll see improvements pretty fast.

comment_text:
The answer, I believe, is mandatory screening, collaboration and AI.  I have celiac disease and was diagnosed at 45 after years of numerous symptoms that didn’t warrant an emergency visit.  Numerous testing, scans, bloodwork, infusions, you name it, I’ve done.  Yet very seldom did anyone have any information about the tests not correlated with their field.  If we can think preventative care and obtain roadmaps to steer us in the right direction, many folks will live longer quality lives.  For me, my genetics showed I carried celiac genes.  Furthermore, my blood had high levels of ttg which were shouting out that I likely had celiac.  But I was never tested or screened.  I could have prevented where I am today had I known.  
My public service announcement, 1% of folks have celiac disease but the average time to get diagnosed is around 8 years.  Celiac has hundreds of various symptoms.  A simple blood test can help determine if you or a family member may have it and avoid devastating effects of not knowing you have this autoimmune disease.

comment_text:
Great 👍🏾 YouTube. I was amazed at how much this “clinician” understood about exercise. Most live in a silos of pharmacology and surgery; sick care not prevention as she pointed out regarding pre diabetes. 
Anyway concerning your glutes there are 3; glute max, glute minimus, and glute minimus. There are also 6 deep rotators you probably need to strengthen. Looking at your SLSA your feet are turning out which means your TFL and lateral gastroc may be hypertonic, glutes too if they hurt. Overcome by running and are weak; they get tired and tighten. Tightness can be a sign of weakness/fatigue. As the doc rightly points out you must strengthen the body for your activity; running. All CV activity through conditioning is consumptive; Catabolic. Strength training complements Cardio and vise versa; one without the other promotes imbalance.  The muscles are protecting themselves when they get tight.
Your knees go into valgus because your adductors are over active, feet are also pronating; confirming. 
Find yourself a NASM trainer who is a Certified Corrective Specialist [CES] who will take you through our OPT program for the assessment the doctor was suggesting. Sorry. Not me, too busy training clients and writing ✍🏼 my first book 📖 
Richard P. MS, NASM, CPT, CES, SFS. GosBless & GodSpeed
